# Python Environment Fix Prompt

Copy and paste the text below into any new Antigravity/VS Code window if you
see the "Select Interpreter" warning or if your terminal is not using the `.venv`.

---

**Prompt to send to Antigravity:**

> "I need to fix my Python environment in this workspace. Please apply these
> 'Nuclear Option' fixes to my [.vscode/settings.json](file:///c:/InnerOrbit-Mobile-Web-App/.vscode/settings.json)
> to ensure the terminal uses my `.venv` and stops showing warnings:
>
> 1. Set `python.defaultInterpreterPath` to the absolute path of my project's
>    [.venv\Scripts\python.exe](file:///c:/InnerOrbit-Mobile-Web-App/.venv/Scripts/python.exe)
>    (use forward slashes `/`).
> 2. Enable `python.terminal.activateEnvironment` and
>    `python.terminal.activateEnvInCurrentTerminal`.
> 3. Disable `python.experiments.enabled`.
> 4. Manually inject the `.venv\Scripts` directory into
>    `terminal.integrated.env.windows.Path` so the terminal is forced to use the
>    virtual environment even if auto-activation fails.
> 5. Define a clean PowerShell profile in `terminal.integrated.profiles.windows`
>    and set it as the default.
>
> Please check if I have a `.venv` first, and then apply these settings."

---

## Why this prompt works

1. **Absolute Paths**: Stops VS Code from guessing where Python is.
2. **Path Injection**: Forces the terminal to use your project's libraries even
   if the visual "decoration" `(.venv)` doesn't show up.
3. **Clean Profile**: Prevents other extensions (like Java or PowerShell Pro)
   from breaking the Python setup.
